<HEADLINE>
TWO TAIWANESE DOCTORS WIN JAPANESE LITERATURE AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tokyo,  May 24 (CNA) 05/25/07  20:45:09 (By Yang Ming-chu and
Y.L. Kao)
</P>
<P>
Books by two Taiwanese doctors have won gold awards for
literature organized by the non-profit Japan Academy Association,
with one of the authors, Chuang Shu- chi, receiving the award in
person Thursday at a presentation ceremony in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The literature awards are awarded to writers aged 50-120 with the
aim of providing hopes and dreams for seniors in the face of an
aging society.
</P>
<P>
The 87-year-old Chuang, a doctor of Chinese medicine, and Chang
Kuei-fang, 95, who is also a doctor, won the awards for their
Japanese-language books on postpartum care and a collection of
personal articles. Their books were selected from among 203
entries.
</P>
<P>
The award organizers praised Chuang, who holds a doctorate in
medical science from Japan's Keio University, for making great
contributions to knowledge and guidance about birth and baby
care.
</P>
<P>
Chang was awarded for her articles depicting goodwill exchanges
between Taiwan and Japan, stories about the late President Chiang
Kai-shek and other historical accounts.
</P>
